{"parse":{"title":"Flying river","pageid":44405876,"revid":776984897,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Campo12Foto_2.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Campo12Foto_2.JPG/220px-Campo12Foto_2.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Campo12Foto_2.JPG/330px-Campo12Foto_2.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Campo12Foto_2.JPG/440px-Campo12Foto_2.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"3072\" data-file-height=\"2304\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Campo12Foto_2.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Aerial view of the Amazon rainforest</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>flying river</b> is a movement of large quantities of <a href=\"/wiki/Water_vapor\" title=\"Water vapor\">water vapor</a> transported in the atmosphere from the <a href=\"/wiki/Amazon_Basin\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Amazon Basin\">Amazon Basin</a> to other parts of South America. The forest trees release water vapor into the atmosphere through <a href=\"/wiki/Transpiration\" title=\"Transpiration\">transpiration</a> and this moisture is deposited in other localities in the form of <a href=\"/wiki/Precipitation\" title=\"Precipitation\">precipitation</a>, forming a virtual river.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Concept\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Concept</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Climatic_consequences_of_deforestation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Climatic consequences of deforestation</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Flying_Rivers_Project\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Flying Rivers Project</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Concept\">Concept</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flying_river&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Concept\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>An average forest tree will release 1000 litres (220&#160;imp&#160;gal; 264&#160;US&#160;gal) of water vapor into the atmosphere every day.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Marull_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Marull-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It has been found that whereas every square metre of the surface of the sea evaporates one litre of water each day, the same area of forest evaporates about eight times as much because of the multiple layers of foliage in the <a href=\"/wiki/Crown_(botany)\" title=\"Crown (botany)\">crown</a> of the trees.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The main airflow in the Amazon basin is towards the southwest. When this air mass reaches the Andes, the mountain range acts as a \"natural barrier\", redirecting huge volumes of humid air towards central and southern Brazil as well as towards northern Argentina, Paraguay, and Uruguay, and rain falls in these areas. Some part of this air manages to surmount the <a href=\"/wiki/Cordillera\" title=\"Cordillera\">cordillera</a> and deposits rain in Peru. Other air masses travel northwards from the Amazon basin, passing over Colombia, Venezuela, Guyana, French Guiana, and Suriname.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Marull_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Marull-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Climatic_consequences_of_deforestation\">Climatic consequences of deforestation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flying_river&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Climatic consequences of deforestation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Mato_Grosso_deforestation_(Pedro_Biondi)_12ago2007.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg/220px-Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"154\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg/330px-Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg/440px-Mato_Grosso_deforestation_%28Pedro_Biondi%29_12ago2007.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2539\" data-file-height=\"1772\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Mato_Grosso_deforestation_(Pedro_Biondi)_12ago2007.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Deforestation in <a href=\"/wiki/Mato_Grosso\" title=\"Mato Grosso\">Mato Grosso</a> state</div></div></div>\n<p>In 2009 Antonio Nobre, a Brazilian climate scientist, stated that without the flying river, much of southern Brazil, which produces approximately 70% of the country's <a href=\"/wiki/Gross_national_product\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gross national product\">GNP</a>, would be arid desert. Clearing the Amazon forest for logging and agriculture is likely to result in lower yields elsewhere. Smoke from the fires set by some farmers to clear land sends particles into the atmosphere, resulting in diminished precipitation, which in turn leaves the trees, which have evolved in wet conditions, vulnerable to fire. The <a href=\"/wiki/Drought\" title=\"Drought\">drought</a> in southern Brazil in 2010 is believed to be due to the drying up of the flying rivers, and the <a href=\"/wiki/2015_Brazilian_drought\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"2015 Brazilian drought\">even worse 2014-5 drought</a> is also attributed to this.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Flying_Rivers_Project\">Flying Rivers Project</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flying_river&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Flying Rivers Project\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>With its large surface area and abundant rainfall, Brazil receives more rain in a year (estimated at 15,000 cubic kilometres (3,600&#160;cu&#160;mi)) than any other country.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Project_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Project-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> In 2007, the Swiss-Brazilian pilot <a href=\"/wiki/G%C3%A9rard_Moss\" title=\"G\u00e9rard Moss\">G\u00e9rard Moss</a> joined with scientists to initiate a project to evaluate the source of the atmospheric water over Brazil and examine the possibility that recent droughts in the country are being caused by the <a href=\"/wiki/Deforestation_of_the_Amazon_rainforest\" title=\"Deforestation of the Amazon rainforest\">deforestation of the Amazon rainforest</a>. This is the Flying Rivers Project. The primary objective of the project is to \"try to ascertain the origin of the water vapour, rainwater and river water in the areas crossed by the flying rivers\". Other objectives are to scientifically evaluate the processes involved in this water transfer and to educate the public in understanding the importance of the Amazon rainforest as a source of the water that is vital for their lives and the economy.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Project_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Project-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Flying_river&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Marull-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Marull_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Marull_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Yana Marull (2012-09-18). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://phys.org/news/2012-09-amazon-vapor-rivers-brazil.html\">\"Amazon's flying water vapor rivers bring rain to Brazil\"</a>. Phys.org<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-11-13</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Amazon%27s+flying+water+vapor+rivers+bring+rain+to+Brazil&amp;rft.pub=Phys.org&amp;rft.date=2012-09-18&amp;rft.au=Yana+Marull&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fphys.org%2Fnews%2F2012-09-amazon-vapor-rivers-brazil.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlying+river\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Thays Prado (2010-03-18). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://planetasustentavel.abril.com.br/noticia/ambiente/rios-voadores-todo-vapor-agua-amazonia-2010-541534.shtml\">\"Rios voadores a todo vapor\"</a> (in Spanish). Planeta Sustent\u00e1vel<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-11-13</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Rios+voadores+a+todo+vapor&amp;rft.pub=Planeta+Sustent%C3%A1vel&amp;rft.date=2010-03-18&amp;rft.au=Thays+Prado&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fplanetasustentavel.abril.com.br%2Fnoticia%2Fambiente%2Frios-voadores-todo-vapor-agua-amazonia-2010-541534.shtml&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlying+river\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Rocha, Jan (2014-09-15). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/sep/15/drought-bites-as-amazons-flying-rivers-dry-up\">\"Drought bites as Amazon's 'flying rivers' dry up\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Guardian\" title=\"The Guardian\">The Guardian</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-11-15</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Guardian&amp;rft.atitle=Drought+bites+as+Amazon%27s+%27flying+rivers%27+dry+up&amp;rft.date=2014-09-15&amp;rft.au=Rocha%2C+Jan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fenvironment%2F2014%2Fsep%2F15%2Fdrought-bites-as-amazons-flying-rivers-dry-up&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFlying+river\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></sp